('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:tips:aa8cac0b', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — 2 to the power of n colours: don''t just double the colour depth", "reading": "<p>Colour depth questions trip students up in one of two directions — going from colour depth to colours, or colours back to colour depth. Both need the SAME rule: <strong>2 to the power of the colour depth</strong>, never the colour depth multiplied by 2.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Direction 1 — colour depth → number of colours:</strong> raise 2 to the power of the given colour depth. A colour depth of 5 bits gives 2<sup>5</sup> = 32 colours, NOT 5 × 2 = 10.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Direction 2 — number of colours → minimum colour depth:</strong> try increasing colour depths and calculate 2<sup>n</sup> for each one until the result is big enough. Needing at least 100 colours? 2<sup>6</sup> = 64 (too few), 2<sup>7</sup> = 128 (enough) — so the minimum colour depth is 7 bits.</p>\n\n<p><strong>The trap to avoid:</strong> confusing colour depth (bits per pixel) with resolution (number of pixels). \"How many colours\" is always a colour depth question; \"how many pixels\" is always a resolution question — they never use the same formula.</p>", "question": "A colour depth of 4 bits is doubled to a colour depth of 8 bits. What happens to the number of possible colours?", "options": ["It rises from 16 to 256, not simply doubling to 32", "It exactly doubles, rising from 16 to 32", "It stays exactly the same at 16 colours", "It rises to 64 colours only, since 8 multiplied by 4 equals 32 which is then halved"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "2 to the power of 4 = 16 and 2 to the power of 8 = 256. Doubling the colour depth does not double the number of colours — it multiplies it by a far bigger factor."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:tips:b8814a77', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — Command-word ladder: ''state'' vs ''explain'' for the quality/size trade-off", "reading": "<p>The same underlying knowledge — that increasing colour depth or resolution affects both quality and file size — is tested at very different tariffs depending on the command word used.</p>\n\n<p><strong>\"State\" (1–2 marks):</strong> a single, direct fact is enough. <em>\"State the effect of increasing an image''s colour depth on its file size.\"</em> → \"It increases the file size.\" One clear statement, no reasoning required.</p>\n\n<p><strong>\"Explain\" (3–4 marks):</strong> needs the full <em>point → …which means… → consequence</em> chain, not just the fact. <em>\"Explain the effect of increasing an image''s colour depth.\"</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Point:</strong> \"A higher colour depth uses more bits to store each pixel''s colour…\"</li>\n<li><strong>…which means…:</strong> \"…so more possible colours can be represented per pixel, giving smoother, more realistic colour…\"</li>\n<li><strong>…but the consequence is…:</strong> \"…while also increasing the overall file size, because more bits are stored for every single pixel in the image.\"</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Why the chain matters:</strong> a bare \"state\" answer scores 0 on an \"explain\" question, because it stops after the first link — the examiner is specifically paying for the \"…which means…\" development, not just the initial fact.</p>", "question": "A 3-mark ''explain'' question asks about the effect of increasing resolution. A student writes only ''It makes the file size bigger.'' How many of the 3 marks would this likely earn?", "options": ["Likely just 1 mark — a bare statement with no development chain", "All 3 marks, since the key fact given is completely correct", "0 marks, because the statement given is factually wrong", "2 marks, for correctly identifying file size as the affected factor"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "An ''explain'' question needs the point developed with a ''which means...'' chain (more pixels → more detail, but also more data to store). A bare fact with no development usually only reaches the first mark."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:fib:ecc5d334', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'fib', 'fib', 1, '{"question": "A bitmap image is made up of a grid of _____, each one storing a binary colour value.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["quadruples", "type", "height", "pixels"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "pixels"}}'::jsonb),
