('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:exam:7cdb6018', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "S1", "question": "<p>Tick (✓) <strong>one</strong> box to identify the correct definition of sampling.</p>", "options": ["Measuring an analogue wave''s amplitude at regular intervals and storing each as binary", "Compressing an audio file so that it takes up less storage space", "Playing back a recorded sound file through a pair of speakers", "Removing background noise from a recording before it is saved"], "hint": "Sampling is about CAPTURING the wave, not compressing or playing it back."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Measuring an analogue wave''s amplitude at regular intervals and storing each as binary</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>How the marks are given</h5>\n<ul>\n<li>Accept cross or other indication as long as it is clear which one box is intended.</li>\n<li>2+ ticks = 0 marks.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": "Measuring an analogue wave''s amplitude at regular intervals and storing each as binary."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:exam:1ae69bea', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "S2", "question": "<p>A recording lasts 3 seconds at a sample rate of 4,000 Hz. Tick (✓) <strong>one</strong> box to identify how many samples are taken in total.</p>", "options": ["12,000 samples", "4,000 samples", "3,000 samples", "7,000 samples"], "hint": "Samples per second × duration in seconds."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>12,000 samples</strong>. Working: 4,000 × 3 = 12,000.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>How the marks are given</h5>\n<ul>\n<li>Only the correct option scores; there is no credit for a value calculated using the wrong method.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": "12,000 samples (4,000 × 3 = 12,000)."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:exam:b939a5b5', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "S5", "question": "<p>A memo is recorded for 6 seconds at a sample rate of 8,000 Hz with an 8-bit depth. Tick (✓) <strong>one</strong> box to identify its file size in bytes.</p>", "options": ["48,000 bytes", "384,000 bytes", "6,000 bytes", "3,000 bytes"], "caseStudy": "<p>A smartphone app lets users record short voice memos, which are saved directly onto the phone''s internal storage before being backed up online.</p>", "hint": "Work out bits first (sample rate × duration × bit depth), then divide by 8 to reach bytes."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>48,000 bytes</strong>. Working: 8,000 × 6 × 8 = 384,000 bits; 384,000 ÷ 8 = 48,000 bytes.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>How the marks are given</h5>\n<ul>\n<li>Only the correct option scores.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": "48,000 bytes (8,000 × 6 × 8 = 384,000 bits; 384,000 ÷ 8 = 48,000 bytes)."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:mcq:3290ba31', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What does ''sample rate'' measure?", "options": ["The number of samples taken from the wave every second", "The number of bits used to store each individual sample", "The total length of a recording, measured in seconds", "The number of separate audio channels a recording uses"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Sample rate is the number of samples taken from the wave every second, measured in Hz."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:mcq:ecec3fd7', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What does ''bit depth'' measure?", "options": ["The number of bits used to store each individual sample", "The number of samples taken from the wave every second", "The total duration of the recording, measured in seconds", "The number of channels used in a stereo recording"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Bit depth is the number of bits used to store the value of each individual sample."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:mcq:1051b8ce', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which unit is sample rate measured in?", "options": ["Hertz (Hz) — the number of samples taken every second", "Bits per second (bps) — the number of bits transferred every second", "Bytes (B) — the total file size once the recording is saved", "Decibels (dB) — a measurement of how loud the recording sounds"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Sample rate is measured in hertz (Hz) — each hertz means one sample taken per second."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:mcq:764e185d', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A recording lasts 2 seconds, using a sample rate of 3,000 Hz. How many samples are taken in total?", "options": ["6,000 samples", "3,000 samples", "1,500 samples", "9,000 samples"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Samples per second × duration = 3,000 × 2 = 6,000 samples."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:mcq:b4643b6a', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A sample is stored using a bit depth of 5 bits. How many different amplitude levels can it represent?", "options": ["32", "16", "8", "64"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "2 to the power of 5 = 32."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:mcq:e687adf8', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Increasing a recording''s sample rate, with bit depth and duration unchanged, has what effect?", "options": ["A closer match to the original wave and a larger file size", "A closer match to the original wave and a smaller file size", "More possible amplitude levels per sample and a larger file size", "No change occurs to either the file size or the playback quality"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A higher sample rate captures the wave more often, giving a closer match to the original — but more samples also means a bigger file."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:mcq:0e61f8f8', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Increasing a recording''s bit depth, with sample rate and duration unchanged, has what effect?", "options": ["More possible amplitude levels per sample and a larger file size", "More possible amplitude levels per sample and a smaller file size", "More samples taken every second and a larger file size", "No change occurs to either the file size or the playback quality"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A higher bit depth gives more levels to round each sample to (better quality) but stores more bits per sample (bigger file)."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:mcq:046ae4e4', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A sound is recorded for 4 seconds at a sample rate of 5,000 Hz with an 8-bit depth. What is the file size in bytes?", "options": ["20,000 bytes", "160,000 bytes", "2,500 bytes", "40,000 bytes"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "5,000 × 4 × 8 = 160,000 bits. 160,000 ÷ 8 = 20,000 bytes."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:mcq:d9c8c5f6', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A sound is recorded for 10 seconds at a sample rate of 4,000 Hz with an 8-bit depth. What is the file size in KB?", "options": ["40 KB", "320 KB", "5 KB", "400 KB"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "4,000 × 10 × 8 = 320,000 bits. 320,000 ÷ 8 = 40,000 bytes. 40,000 ÷ 1,000 = 40 KB."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:mcq:744986d1', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A 2-second mono recording at 8,000 Hz with an 8-bit depth is 16 KB. What would the SAME recording be, in KB, if recorded in stereo instead?", "options": ["32 KB", "16 KB", "8 KB", "64 KB"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A stereo recording doubles the mono file size: 16 KB × 2 = 32 KB."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:mcq:29b07a9b', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which statement about analogue and digital sound is correct?", "options": ["Analogue sound is continuous; sampling converts it into a stream of binary numbers", "Analogue sound is already stored as binary numbers before any sampling ever takes place", "Sampling converts an already-digital recording back into a continuous analogue wave again", "A microphone stores sound directly as a fixed sample rate and bit depth, with no wave"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Analogue sound is a continuous wave; sampling measures it at intervals and stores each measurement as binary — the reverse of options 2 and 3."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:mcq:9cd8df1a', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A memory card can hold 2,000 KB of audio. Each mono recording made on it is 40 KB. Roughly how many of these recordings will fit?", "options": ["50 recordings", "20 recordings", "80 recordings", "500 recordings"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "2,000 ÷ 40 = 50 recordings."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:tf:434ef643', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Sound is an analogue signal before it is sampled."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — real sound is a continuous analogue wave; sampling converts it into digital data."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:tf:13ab436b', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Sample rate measures the number of bits used to store each sample."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "That describes bit depth, not sample rate. Sample rate is the number of samples taken every second, measured in Hz."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:tf:dbe46214', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A higher sample rate always produces a larger file, for the same duration and bit depth."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — more samples per second means more values to store, so the file size increases."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:tf:f038a2d7', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A higher bit depth means each sample can be rounded to more possible amplitude levels."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — a bit depth of n bits gives 2 to the power of n possible levels, so more bits means more levels."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:tf:13103e86', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Increasing bit depth improves quality with no effect on file size."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "There is always a trade-off — more bits stored per sample also increases the file size."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:tf:9ddb30ad', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The sound file-size formula is sample rate × duration × bit depth."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — file size in bits = sample rate × duration × bit depth."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:tf:d2b14bd2', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A stereo recording''s file size is calculated using exactly the same formula as a mono recording, with no adjustment."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "A stereo recording stores two channels, so its file size is double the mono formula''s result (× 2)."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:tf:1d9c0d52', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A file-size calculation using the sound formula should be left in bits as the final answer, even if the question asks for KB."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "The formula gives bits first, but that is only the first step — convert (÷8 for bytes, ÷1,000 per unit after that) into whatever unit the question actually asks for."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:learn:4e46b9c8', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How is analogue sound turned into digital data?", "reading": "<h4>Analogue sound, digital storage</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Real sound is an <strong>analogue</strong> signal — a smooth, continuous wave whose <strong>amplitude</strong> (its height, which corresponds to loudness) can take literally any value as it changes over time.</li>\n<li>A computer can only store <strong>binary</strong> data, so a continuous analogue wave cannot be stored directly — it has to be converted into a stream of binary numbers first. This process is called <strong>sampling</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>What actually happens during sampling</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>An analogue-to-digital converter measures the wave''s <strong>amplitude</strong> at <strong>regular, fixed time intervals</strong> — one snapshot after another along the wave.</li>\n<li>Each individual measurement (a <strong>sample</strong>) is rounded to the nearest value that can be represented in binary, and stored as a <strong>binary number</strong>.</li>\n<li>Played back in order, one after another, these stored samples recreate an approximation of the original analogue wave — never a perfect copy, because sampling can only capture the wave''s height at particular instants, not every instant in between.</li>\n</ul>\n<svg viewBox=\"0 0 290 140\" width=\"290\" height=\"140\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"A sound wave with six evenly spaced vertical sample lines, each ending in a dot showing the amplitude measured at that instant\">\n<line x1=\"10\" y1=\"130\" x2=\"280\" y2=\"130\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" opacity=\"0.35\"/>\n<polyline points=\"10,70 45,25 80,115 115,25 150,115 185,25 220,115 255,25 280,70\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2.5\"/>\n<line x1=\"10\" y1=\"130\" x2=\"10\" y2=\"70\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke-dasharray=\"3,3\" opacity=\"0.6\"/>\n<line x1=\"64\" y1=\"130\" x2=\"64\" y2=\"74\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke-dasharray=\"3,3\" opacity=\"0.6\"/>\n<line x1=\"118\" y1=\"130\" x2=\"118\" y2=\"33\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke-dasharray=\"3,3\" opacity=\"0.6\"/>\n<line x1=\"172\" y1=\"130\" x2=\"172\" y2=\"58\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke-dasharray=\"3,3\" opacity=\"0.6\"/>\n<line x1=\"226\" y1=\"130\" x2=\"226\" y2=\"100\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke-dasharray=\"3,3\" opacity=\"0.6\"/>\n<line x1=\"280\" y1=\"130\" x2=\"280\" y2=\"70\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke-dasharray=\"3,3\" opacity=\"0.6\"/>\n<circle cx=\"10\" cy=\"70\" r=\"4\" fill=\"currentColor\"/>\n<circle cx=\"64\" cy=\"74\" r=\"4\" fill=\"currentColor\"/>\n<circle cx=\"118\" cy=\"33\" r=\"4\" fill=\"currentColor\"/>\n<circle cx=\"172\" cy=\"58\" r=\"4\" fill=\"currentColor\"/>\n<circle cx=\"226\" cy=\"100\" r=\"4\" fill=\"currentColor\"/>\n<circle cx=\"280\" cy=\"70\" r=\"4\" fill=\"currentColor\"/>\n</svg>\n<p>The dashed lines mark six regular instants in time; the dot on each one is the sample taken at that instant. Notice how much of the wave''s shape between the dots is simply never recorded — that missing detail is exactly what a higher sample rate reduces.</p>\n<h4>Why \"approximation\" matters</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Because sampling only measures the wave at intervals, some information between samples is always lost. The more often — and more precisely — you sample, the closer the digital copy gets to the original. That is the whole idea behind sample rate and bit depth, covered next.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Why must an analogue sound wave be sampled before a computer can store it?", "options": ["A computer can only store binary data, so the wave must be converted into binary numbers", "Sampling is a compression technique that shrinks the file so it takes up far less storage space", "Microphones only ever produce a digital electrical signal, so no conversion is required at all", "Sampling instantly removes background noise from a recording before it is saved as a file"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A computer can only store binary data. Sound starts out as a continuous analogue wave, so it must be sampled — measured at regular intervals and each measurement stored as binary — before it can be stored at all."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:learn:6d6dc06b', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Sample rate: how often the wave is measured", "reading": "<h4>Sample rate: how often the wave is measured</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Sample rate</strong> is the number of samples taken from the analogue wave <strong>every second</strong>, measured in <strong>hertz (Hz)</strong> (or kilohertz, kHz, where 1 kHz = 1,000 Hz).</li>\n<li>A sample rate of 8,000 Hz means the wave''s amplitude is measured 8,000 separate times, evenly spaced, within a single second of audio.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Higher sample rate = closer to the original wave</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The wave is constantly changing between samples, and none of that in-between detail is captured — it simply is not recorded at all.</li>\n<li>Taking MORE samples per second means the gaps between measurements are smaller, so less of the original wave''s detail is missed. The digital copy ends up a closer match to the real analogue sound — higher playback quality.</li>\n<li>Taking FEWER samples per second leaves bigger gaps, so more detail is lost, and the digital version is a rougher approximation of the original — this can be heard as a noticeably lower-quality recording.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Higher sample rate = bigger file</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Every extra sample taken is another value that has to be stored as a binary number. A higher sample rate therefore always produces MORE samples for the same length of recording, which means a LARGER file size.</li>\n</ul>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Sample rate</th><th>Samples taken in 1 second</th></tr>\n<tr><td>4,000 Hz</td><td>4,000 samples</td></tr>\n<tr><td>8,000 Hz</td><td>8,000 samples</td></tr>\n<tr><td>44,100 Hz (44.1 kHz)</td><td>44,100 samples</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>44.1 kHz is the sample rate used for standard audio CDs — a real-world example of a high sample rate chosen for good playback quality.</p>", "question": "A recording uses a sample rate of 6,000 Hz. How many samples are taken from the wave in 2 seconds?", "options": ["12,000 samples", "6,000 samples", "3,000 samples", "18,000 samples"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Samples per second × duration = 6,000 × 2 = 12,000 samples."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:learn:38d86582', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Bit depth: how precisely each sample is measured", "reading": "<h4>Bit depth: how precisely each sample is measured</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Bit depth</strong> (also called <strong>sample resolution</strong>) is the number of <strong>bits</strong> used to store the value of <strong>each individual sample</strong>.</li>\n<li>The number of bits available decides how many different amplitude values a single sample can be rounded to — a bit depth of n bits gives <strong>2<sup>n</sup></strong> possible levels, exactly the same \"2 to the power of n\" rule used for colour depth in images.</li>\n</ul>\n<svg viewBox=\"0 0 230 180\" width=\"230\" height=\"180\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Two vertical boxes comparing bit depth: a 2-bit box divided into 4 equal amplitude levels, and a 3-bit box divided into 8 equal amplitude levels, showing that more bits give more possible levels\">\n<rect x=\"10\" y=\"10\" width=\"90\" height=\"160\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"10\" y1=\"50\" x2=\"100\" y2=\"50\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<line x1=\"10\" y1=\"90\" x2=\"100\" y2=\"90\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<line x1=\"10\" y1=\"130\" x2=\"100\" y2=\"130\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<rect x=\"130\" y=\"10\" width=\"90\" height=\"160\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"130\" y1=\"30\" x2=\"220\" y2=\"30\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<line x1=\"130\" y1=\"50\" x2=\"220\" y2=\"50\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<line x1=\"130\" y1=\"70\" x2=\"220\" y2=\"70\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<line x1=\"130\" y1=\"90\" x2=\"220\" y2=\"90\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<line x1=\"130\" y1=\"110\" x2=\"220\" y2=\"110\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<line x1=\"130\" y1=\"130\" x2=\"220\" y2=\"130\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n<line x1=\"130\" y1=\"150\" x2=\"220\" y2=\"150\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n</svg>\n<p>Left: a 2-bit depth gives 2<sup>2</sup> = 4 possible amplitude levels for each sample. Right: a 3-bit depth gives 2<sup>3</sup> = 8 possible levels — roughly double the levels for just one extra bit, letting each sample record the wave''s true height far more precisely.</p>\n<h4>Higher bit depth = closer to the original wave</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>With only a few possible levels, each sample has to be rounded to the nearest available level, which can be some distance from the wave''s real height at that instant — this rounding error is heard as background hiss or distortion.</li>\n<li>A higher bit depth gives many more levels to round to, so each sample sits much closer to the wave''s true amplitude, giving a cleaner, higher-quality recording.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Higher bit depth = bigger file</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Every sample stored using MORE bits takes up MORE space, regardless of the sample rate or duration. A higher bit depth therefore always produces a LARGER file size, for exactly the same recording.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A sample is stored using a bit depth of 4 bits. How many different amplitude levels can that sample be rounded to?", "options": ["16", "8", "4", "32"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "2 to the power of 4 = 16 possible levels."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:learn:554c0fb7', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Quality vs file size: the trade-off from sample rate and bit depth", "reading": "<h4>Both factors push quality and file size the same way</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Increasing <strong>sample rate</strong> captures the wave more often, giving a closer match to the original — but it means more samples are taken for the same length of recording, so the file gets <strong>bigger</strong>.</li>\n<li>Increasing <strong>bit depth</strong> allows each sample to be measured more precisely — but it means more bits are stored for every single sample, so the file gets <strong>bigger</strong> too.</li>\n<li>There is no way to improve playback quality using either factor without also increasing the file size — it is always a trade-off, exactly as with colour depth and resolution for images.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Worked example: doubling the sample rate</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Step</th><th>What you do</th><th>Result</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>A 4-second recording uses a sample rate of 5,000 Hz and a bit depth of 8 bits. Find the file size in bits, then bytes, then KB.</td><td>5,000 × 4 × 8 = 160,000 bits → 20,000 bytes → 20 KB</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>Double ONLY the sample rate to 10,000 Hz, keeping duration and bit depth the same. Recalculate.</td><td>10,000 × 4 × 8 = 320,000 bits → 40,000 bytes → 40 KB</td></tr>\n<tr><td>3</td><td>Compare the two file sizes.</td><td>40 KB is exactly double the original 20 KB</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h4>Why this differs from the image-doubling trap</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Doubling ONE sound factor (sample rate) doubles the file size directly — the sound formula multiplies three separate factors together, so doubling any ONE of them (sample rate, duration or bit depth) doubles the file size. This is different from an image, where doubling BOTH height and width together roughly quadruples the file size.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A recording''s file size is 20 KB. If you double ONLY the bit depth, keeping sample rate and duration the same, what is the new approximate file size?", "options": ["40 KB", "20 KB", "80 KB", "10 KB"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Doubling any single factor in sample rate × duration × bit depth doubles the file size: 20 KB × 2 = 40 KB."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:learn:2a136f14', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Worked example: calculating a sound file''s size", "reading": "<h4>The formula</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>File size (bits) = sample rate (Hz) × duration (seconds) × bit depth (bits)</strong></li>\n<li>Always calculate the answer in <strong>bits</strong> first, then convert into whatever unit the question actually asks for.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Worked example</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Step</th><th>What you do</th><th>Result</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>A 5-second recording is sampled at 8,000 Hz with an 8-bit depth. Multiply sample rate × duration × bit depth.</td><td>8,000 × 5 × 8 = 320,000 bits</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>Convert bits into bytes by dividing by 8.</td><td>320,000 ÷ 8 = 40,000 bytes</td></tr>\n<tr><td>3</td><td>Convert bytes into a sensible unit by dividing by 1,000.</td><td>40,000 ÷ 1,000 = 40 KB</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h4>Show every step, every time</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>OCR-style marking usually splits calculation marks between the <strong>working</strong> and the <strong>final answer</strong> — so writing down all three steps (multiply, then ÷8, then ÷1,000) protects your marks even if you slip on the arithmetic somewhere along the way.</li>\n<li>Unless a question tells you otherwise, this formula assumes a single (<strong>mono</strong>) recording channel — see the next section for what changes with stereo sound.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A sound is recorded for 3 seconds at a sample rate of 4,000 Hz with a bit depth of 8 bits. What is the file size in KB?", "options": ["12 KB", "96 KB", "1.5 KB", "1,200 KB"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "4,000 × 3 × 8 = 96,000 bits. 96,000 ÷ 8 = 12,000 bytes. 12,000 ÷ 1,000 = 12 KB."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:learn:a5d12ac5', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Mono vs stereo: an extra factor in the formula", "reading": "<h4>Mono: one channel, the formula as given</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>mono</strong> (single-channel) recording stores just ONE stream of samples, so the file size is exactly sample rate × duration × bit depth, with nothing extra to add.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Stereo: two channels, double the data</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>stereo</strong> recording stores TWO separate channels of samples at once (a \"left\" channel and a \"right\" channel, which is what lets headphones produce a sense of direction). Each channel is sampled using exactly the same sample rate and bit depth.</li>\n<li>Because there are two complete streams of samples instead of one, a stereo recording''s file size is exactly <strong>double</strong> the mono formula''s result: <strong>sample rate × duration × bit depth × 2</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Worked example</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Step</th><th>What you do</th><th>Result</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>The same 5-second, 8,000 Hz, 8-bit recording from before is instead recorded in STEREO. Calculate the mono size in bits first.</td><td>8,000 × 5 × 8 = 320,000 bits</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>Multiply by 2 for the second (stereo) channel.</td><td>320,000 × 2 = 640,000 bits</td></tr>\n<tr><td>3</td><td>Convert to bytes, then KB, as normal.</td><td>640,000 ÷ 8 = 80,000 bytes; ÷ 1,000 = 80 KB</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h4>Only apply the ×2 when the question says stereo</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Unless a question specifically tells you the recording is in stereo, always assume <strong>mono</strong> and use the plain formula with no ×2. Adding an unrequested ×2 — or forgetting a genuinely stereo one — is one of the most common slips on this topic.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A 2-second recording uses a sample rate of 10,000 Hz and an 8-bit depth, recorded in STEREO. What is its file size in KB?", "options": ["40 KB", "20 KB", "10 KB", "80 KB"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Mono: 10,000 × 2 × 8 = 160,000 bits → 20,000 bytes → 20 KB. Stereo doubles this: 20 × 2 = 40 KB."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:misc:a4f1459c', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking sample rate and bit depth measure the same thing.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> <strong>Sample rate</strong> is how OFTEN the wave is measured (samples per second, in Hz). <strong>Bit depth</strong> is how PRECISELY each individual sample is measured (bits per sample). They are two separate, independent factors.</p>", "question": "Which statement correctly distinguishes sample rate from bit depth?", "options": ["Sample rate is samples per second; bit depth is bits used per sample", "Sample rate and bit depth both measure exactly the same thing", "Bit depth is samples per second; sample rate is bits used per sample instead", "Sample rate measures loudness; bit depth measures the recording''s duration"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Sample rate = how often (Hz); bit depth = how precisely (bits per sample) — two separate properties of a digital recording."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:misc:17d31356', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking a bit depth of n bits gives n possible amplitude levels — e.g. assuming 4 bits means 4 levels.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> It is <strong>2 to the power of n</strong>, not n. A bit depth of 4 bits gives 2<sup>4</sup> = <strong>16</strong> possible levels, not 4 — exactly the same rule used for colour depth in images.</p>", "question": "A bit depth of 4 bits is used. How many different amplitude levels can each sample represent?", "options": ["4", "8", "16", "20"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "2 to the power of 4 = 16, not 4. Bit depth and number of levels are related by 2 to the power of n, not a simple count."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:misc:537c4c3d', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Leaving a sound file-size calculation answer in bits, because the multiplication already produced ''a number'' that looks like an answer.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Sample rate × duration × bit depth always gives the answer in <strong>bits</strong> first — that is only the first step. You must then divide by 8 to reach bytes, and keep dividing by 1,000 for each unit up the ladder until you reach the unit the question actually asked for.</p>", "question": "A calculation gives 160,000 bits, and the question asks for the answer in KB. What should you do next?", "options": ["Divide by 8 to get bytes, then divide by 1,000 to get KB", "Write down 160,000 as the final answer, already correct in KB", "Multiply the bits total by 8 to reach bytes", "Divide the bits total by 1,000 only, then stop working"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "160,000 bits ÷ 8 = 20,000 bytes, then ÷ 1,000 = 20 KB. Both conversion steps are needed to reach the unit asked for."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:misc:edd0e40b', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Forgetting to double the file size for a stereo recording, or doubling one that is actually mono.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Only apply <strong>×2</strong> when a question specifically says the recording is <strong>stereo</strong> (two channels). A plain sample-rate × duration × bit-depth calculation already assumes <strong>mono</strong> (one channel) unless told otherwise.</p>", "question": "A question gives a sample rate, duration and bit depth but does not mention stereo or mono. Which should you assume?", "options": ["Mono — use the plain formula with no ×2", "Stereo — always multiply the plain formula by 2", "It cannot be calculated without being told which one it is", "Both channels — divide the plain formula by 2 instead"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Unless a question specifically states the recording is stereo, assume mono and use the plain formula (no ×2)."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:misc:3a116eea', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Believing that increasing sample rate only affects file size with no effect on quality, or that bit depth only affects quality with no effect on file size.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Both factors affect BOTH things. A higher sample rate AND a higher bit depth each improve playback quality AND increase file size — neither factor affects only one of the two.</p>", "question": "Which statement about sample rate and bit depth is correct?", "options": ["Both factors affect quality AND file size, not just one or the other", "Sample rate only ever affects file size; bit depth only ever affects quality", "Bit depth only ever affects file size; sample rate only ever affects quality", "Neither sample rate nor bit depth has any real effect on quality at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Both sample rate and bit depth affect BOTH playback quality and file size — that is exactly why the topic is a trade-off."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:misc:e3ddcf1d', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Assuming sound is already stored as binary before it reaches the computer, so no conversion process is needed.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Real sound is an <strong>analogue</strong> signal — a continuous wave, not binary data. It must be <strong>sampled</strong> (its amplitude measured at regular intervals and each measurement stored as a binary number) before a computer can store it at all.</p>", "question": "Why can''t a computer store an analogue sound wave directly, without first sampling it?", "options": ["The wave is continuous, but computers can only store data as binary numbers", "Microphones are only ever able to physically produce a binary electrical signal", "Analogue sound waves cannot physically be recorded by any microphone at all", "Computers can already store analogue waves directly, so sampling is not needed"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Analogue sound is a continuous signal; a computer can only store binary data, so the wave must be sampled and each measurement stored as a binary number."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:tips:03473a88', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — Show-your-working ladder: the sound file-size calculation", "reading": "<p>A typical question: <em>\"A recording lasts 3 seconds, sampled at 5,000 Hz with an 8-bit depth. Calculate the file size in bytes. Show your working.\"</em> [2 marks] Here is the same answer at every level:</p>\n\n<p><strong>❌ 0 marks:</strong> \"15,000 bytes\"</p>\n<ul>\n<li>No working shown. Even a correct final answer with nothing behind it risks losing the working mark entirely if it happens to be wrong.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>⚠️ 1 mark:</strong> \"5,000 × 3 × 8 = 120,000\"</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Valid working is shown (1 mark), but the answer was never converted into bytes and stated as a final answer — the second mark is for the CONVERTED answer in the unit asked for.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>✅ 2 marks:</strong> \"5,000 × 3 × 8 = 120,000 bits <strong>(1)</strong>. 120,000 ÷ 8 = 15,000 bytes <strong>(1)</strong>.\"</p>\n\n<p><strong>Why this matters even if your arithmetic slips:</strong> OCR-style marking separates the WORKING mark from the ANSWER mark. If your method is correct but you slip on the final division, you can still keep the working mark — but only if you actually wrote the working down.</p>", "question": "You calculate 5,000 × 3 × 8 = 120,000 correctly, but then wrongly divide by 100 instead of 8 and write ''1,200 bytes''. What mark do you get out of 2?", "options": ["0, because the final stated answer is wrong", "1 — the working mark for the correct multiplication step", "2, since your working clearly shows you understood the method", "It depends entirely on which calculator you used"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The multiplication step (5,000 × 3 × 8 = 120,000 bits) is valid working, so it earns the working mark even though the final conversion — and therefore the answer mark — was wrong."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:tips:479bf9c7', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — 2 to the power of n levels: don''t just double the bit depth", "reading": "<p>Bit depth questions trip students up in one of two directions — going from bit depth to levels, or levels back to bit depth. Both need the SAME rule: <strong>2 to the power of the bit depth</strong>, never the bit depth multiplied by 2.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Direction 1 — bit depth → number of levels:</strong> raise 2 to the power of the given bit depth. A bit depth of 5 bits gives 2<sup>5</sup> = 32 levels, NOT 5 × 2 = 10.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Direction 2 — number of levels → minimum bit depth:</strong> try increasing bit depths and calculate 2<sup>n</sup> for each one until the result is big enough. Needing at least 100 levels? 2<sup>6</sup> = 64 (too few), 2<sup>7</sup> = 128 (enough) — so the minimum bit depth is 7 bits.</p>\n\n<p><strong>The trap to avoid:</strong> confusing bit depth (precision of each sample) with sample rate (how often samples are taken). \"How many levels\" is always a bit depth question; \"how many samples per second\" is always a sample-rate question — they never use the same formula.</p>", "question": "A bit depth of 3 bits is doubled to a bit depth of 6 bits. What happens to the number of possible amplitude levels?", "options": ["It rises from 8 to 64, not simply doubling to 16", "It exactly doubles, rising from 8 to 16", "It stays exactly the same at 8 levels", "It rises to 24 levels only, since 3 multiplied by 6 equals 18 which is then rounded"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "2 to the power of 3 = 8 and 2 to the power of 6 = 64. Doubling the bit depth does not double the number of levels — it multiplies it by a far bigger factor."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound:tips:67551eb7', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-7-data-storage-sound', '1.2.7 Data Storage: Sound', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — Command-word ladder: ''state'' vs ''explain'' for the quality/size trade-off", "reading": "<p>The same underlying knowledge — that increasing sample rate or bit depth affects both quality and file size — is tested at very different tariffs depending on the command word used.</p>\n\n<p><strong>\"State\" (1–2 marks):</strong> a single, direct fact is enough. <em>\"State the effect of increasing a recording''s sample rate on its file size.\"</em> → \"It increases the file size.\" One clear statement, no reasoning required.</p>\n\n<p><strong>\"Explain\" (3–4 marks):</strong> needs the full <em>point → …which means… → consequence</em> chain, not just the fact. <em>\"Explain the effect of increasing a recording''s sample rate.\"</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Point:</strong> \"A higher sample rate takes more samples of the wave every second…\"</li>\n<li><strong>…which means…:</strong> \"…so less of the original wave''s detail is missed between samples, giving a closer match to the original sound…\"</li>\n<li><strong>…but the consequence is…:</strong> \"…while also increasing the overall file size, because more samples have to be stored for the same length of recording.\"</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Why the chain matters:</strong> a bare \"state\" answer scores 0 on an \"explain\" question, because it stops after the first link — the examiner is specifically paying for the \"…which means…\" development, not just the initial fact.</p>", "question": "A 3-mark ''explain'' question asks about the effect of increasing bit depth. A student writes only ''It makes the file size bigger.'' How many of the 3 marks would this likely earn?", "options": ["Likely just 1 mark — a bare statement with no development chain", "All 3 marks, since the key fact given is completely correct", "0 marks, because the statement given is factually wrong", "2 marks, for correctly identifying file size as the affected factor"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "An ''explain'' question needs the point developed with a ''which means...'' chain (more bits → more precise levels, but also more data to store). A bare fact with no development usually only reaches the first mark."}'::jsonb),
